%N A390117 Least integer m > 1 such that m*n + 1 is a prime.
%C A390117 Clearly, a(n) >= A034693(n).
%C A390117 Conjecture: (i) a(n) <= 2*sqrt(n+6) for all n > 0.
%C A390117 (ii) For any n > 0, there is a positive integer m <= 2*sqrt(n+3) such that m*n - 1 is prime.
%C A390117 If p = m*n + 1 is prime with 1 < m <= n, then m*(n+1) = p + m - 1 and (m-1)*(n+1) = m*n + m - n - 1 < p, hence by Lucas' theorem we have C(m*(n+1)^2,m*(n+1)) = C(p*(n+1)+(m-1)(n+1),p+m-1) == C(n+1,1)*C((m-1)(n+1),m-1) (mod p) and thus p does not divide C(m*(n+1)^2,m*(n+1)).
%C A390117 Similarly, if p = m*n - 1 is an odd prime with m > 0, then by Lucas' theorem C(m*n^2,m*n) = C(p*n+n,p+1) is not divided by p.
%H A390117 Zhi-Wei Sun, <a href="/A390117/b390117.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
